  "text": "Kubernetes RBAC Authorization Implementation Overview\n\nThe RBAC (Role-Based Access Control) authorization system in Kubernetes is implemented across multiple packages and files, orchestrating a sophisticated hierarchy of role resolution, policy enforcement, and escalation prevention. Here's a comprehensive breakdown of the key components:\n\n## Core Authorization Engine\n\nThe RBACAuthorizer (plugin/pkg/auth/authorizer/rbac/rbac.go:50) is the primary authorizer that implements the authorizer.Authorizer interface. Its Authorize method (line 75) evaluates requests against policies by delegating to a RequestToRuleMapper (line 37), which provides the interface for retrieving PolicyRules that apply to users. The authorizer uses an authorizingVisitor pattern to check rules and short-circuit on first allow.\n\n## Rule Resolution Hierarchy\n\nThe DefaultRuleResolver (pkg/registry/rbac/validation/rule.go:91) is the concrete implementation of AuthorizationRuleResolver (line 37) that resolves all PolicyRules applicable to a user in a namespace. It implements:\n- RulesFor (line 118): Returns accumulated PolicyRules for a user\n- VisitRulesFor (line 179): Visits rules for a user across ClusterRoleBindings and RoleBindings\n- GetRoleReferenceRules (line 240): Resolves Role/ClusterRole references from role bindings\n\nThe resolver depends on four getter/lister interfaces:\n- RoleGetter (line 102): Fetches Role objects\n- RoleBindingLister (line 106): Lists RoleBindings in a namespace\n- ClusterRoleGetter (line 110): Fetches ClusterRole objects  \n- ClusterRoleBindingLister (line 114): Lists ClusterRoleBindings cluster-wide\n\nIn practice, these are implemented by adapter types in rbac.go (lines 195-225) that wrap informer listers.\n\n## Subject Access Evaluation\n\nThe SubjectAccessEvaluator (plugin/pkg/auth/authorizer/rbac/subject_locator.go:42) implements SubjectLocator and provides the AllowedSubjects method (line 64) that returns which subjects (users, groups, service accounts) have permissions to perform an action. It traverses both cluster-wide and namespace-scoped role bindings, matching rules against the provided request attributes.\n\n## Subject Access Review REST Handler\n\nThe REST handler (pkg/registry/authorization/subjectaccessreview/rest.go:35) implements a StatelessCreateRest that handles SubjectAccessReview API requests. Its Create method (line 63) validates the request and uses the authorizer to evaluate the decision, then returns a SubjectAccessReviewStatus with allowed/denied/reason fields.\n\n## Bootstrap RBAC Policies\n\nBootstrap policies are defined in plugin/pkg/auth/authorizer/rbac/bootstrappolicy/ with three main modules:\n\n1. policy.go: Defines ClusterRoles() (line 197) and ClusterRoleBindings() that provide core system permissions for components like system:kube-scheduler, system:kube-controller-manager. Also includes NodeRules() (line 112) for kubelet permissions.\n\n2. namespace_policy.go: Provides NamespaceRoles() and NamespaceRoleBindings() for namespace-scoped default roles in system namespaces (kube-system, kube-public, etc.).\n\n3. controller_policy.go: Defines ControllerRoles() and ControllerRoleBindings() for various controller service accounts (replication-controller, horizontal-pod-autoscaler, etc.).\n\nThese policies are reconciled at startup via PostStartHook in pkg/registry/rbac/rest/storage_rbac.go (line 131).\n\n## Escalation Prevention\n\nThe escalation prevention system is implemented through multiple mechanisms:\n\n1. escalation_check.go provides three key functions:\n   - EscalationAllowed (line 32): Checks if user is in system:masters group\n   - RoleEscalationAuthorized (line 55): Checks if user has \"escalate\" verb on role/clusterrole resources\n   - BindingAuthorized (line 101): Checks if user has \"bind\" verb on the specific role being referenced\n\n2. Validation via ConfirmNoEscalation (pkg/registry/rbac/validation/rule.go:53) checks that a user attempting to create/update a role/binding doesn't grant permissions they don't already have.\n\n## Policy-Based Storage Implementation\n\nThe four policy-based storage implementations wrap the standard storage and enforce escalation prevention at the storage layer:\n\n1. pkg/registry/rbac/role/policybased/storage.go: For Role objects\n2. pkg/registry/rbac/rolebinding/policybased/storage.go: For RoleBinding objects\n3. pkg/registry/rbac/clusterrole/policybased/storage.go: For ClusterRole objects (with special handling for aggregationRule requiring cluster-admin)\n4. pkg/registry/rbac/clusterrolebinding/policybased/storage.go: For ClusterRoleBinding objects\n\nEach Storage type wraps rest.StandardStorage and intercepts Create and Update operations. They check escalation permissions before delegating to the underlying storage, using either:\n- EscalationAllowed() for system:masters bypass\n- RoleEscalationAuthorized() for explicit escalate permission\n- BindingAuthorized() for role binding-specific checks\n- ConfirmNoEscalation() to verify the user already possesses the permissions being granted\n\n## Integration Points\n\nThe RESTStorageProvider (pkg/registry/rbac/rest/storage_rbac.go:61) orchestrates the entire storage setup:\n1. Creates base storage instances for roles, rolebindings, clusterroles, clusterrolebindings\n2. Wraps them with policy-based storage implementations\n3. Creates a DefaultRuleResolver for escalation validation\n4. Registers the PostStartHook for bootstrap policy reconciliation\n\nThe authorizer configuration (pkg/kubeapiserver/authorizer/config.go:123) instantiates the RBACAuthorizer with RoleGetter/RoleBindingLister/ClusterRoleGetter/ClusterRoleBindingLister adapters that fetch data from informers, enabling real-time authorization decisions based on current cluster state."
